{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17500967","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17500967"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T10:20:58+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T10:20:58+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1702"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1702","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1702"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.12,0.38,0.23,0.05,0.22]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1702"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"109702"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1702","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1702"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1702"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"92098"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"5"},{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"31"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"251"},{"type":"tags","id":"517"},{"type":"tags","id":"1052"},{"type":"tags","id":"3549"},{"type":"tags","id":"4964"},{"type":"tags","id":"5771"},{"type":"tags","id":"9598"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"1383"},{"type":"contributions","id":"11823"},{"type":"contributions","id":"41136"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43849"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44775"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"109702","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/109702"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 57-year-old man presents with a four-day history of vomiting. The vomitus is clear-coloured and contains recognisable particles of food eaten several hours earlier. Over the last six weeks, he has noticed upper abdominal pain that goes through to his back. Over this time period, he has lost 6kg in weight. Ten years ago he was treated for a duodenal ulcer with ranitidine. He does not smoke or drink. On examination, his blood pressure is 110/70 mmHg and pulse 90/min. His abdomen is soft and not distended. A succussion splash is present. Faecal occult blood testing is negative.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Carcinoma of the cardia","Carcinoma of the antrum","Carcinoma of the duodenum","Chronic duodenal ulcer disease","Carcinoma of the pancreas"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient has a gastric outlet obstruction, a diagnosis that can be derived from the history alone. The recognition of recognisable articles of food that were consumed hours earlier implies that there is a gastric hold-up with no digestive process occurring. Most of these patients will present with weight loss, postprandial satiety and non-bilious vomiting. If there is a large volume of liquid gastric contents, a succussion splash may be detected. In other words, when the abdomen is shaken from side to side, the retained fluid in the stomach can be heard (and felt) moving about in the distended and obstructed stomach. An abdominal X-ray may reveal a dilated stomach with air-fluid levels. The diagnosis and the underlying cause can usually be confirmed with an oesophagogastroduodenoscopy, provided that there is not too much gastric content to obscure the view. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe most common cause of obstruction would be cancer in the distal stomach (ie \u003Cstrong\u003Ecarcinoma of the antrum\u003C/strong\u003E). In the days before proton-pump inhibitors and the development of effective Helicobacter pylori eradication, peptic ulcer disease was the most common cause of gastric outlet obstruction. Other causes, such as carcinoma of the duodenum, Crohn\u0027s disease and strictures secondary to caustic agent ingestion, are very rare.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ECarcinoma of the pancreas may present with epigastric pain that radiates to the back. However, carcinoma of the head of the pancreas is much more likely to present with obstructive jaundice before any duodenal obstruction becomes evident. Tumours of the body and the tail of the pancreas would not produce any gastric outlet obstruction. Carcinoma of the cardia usually presents with dysphagia and weight loss. Carcinoma of the duodenum is a very rare condition. In terms of the likelihood of causing this patient\u2019s current problem, it is far outweighed by carcinoma of the distal stomach.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["A succussion splash is often a sign of malignant upper gastrointestinal tract obstruction."],"references":["Khullar S, DiSario J. Gastric Outlet Obstruction. Gastrointestinal Endoscopy Clinics of North America. 1996;6(3):585-603. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/8803569/","Appasani S, Kochhar S, Nagi B, Gupta V, Kochhar R. Benign gastric outlet obstruction--spectrum and management. Trop Gastroenterol. 2011;32(4):259-66. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/22696905/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"92098"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1702"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"92098","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/92098"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-07-24T22:28:29+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-07-24T22:29:34+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1702"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"109702"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"5","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/5"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\u